Introduction

Published in October 2020, the TUAT Insecta database was compiled from various plant and insect databases and journal articles and includes insect-host plant relationships, host plant-metabolite relationships, and metabolite functions. Taxonomic information ranging from species to Kingdom is available for both the insects and host plants. Metabolites are identified by chemical name, molecular formula, and cid.

Additional information is intergrated from the webchem: Chemical Information from the Web and divides the metabolites into classes and subclasses 1,2,3 and 4.

This database holds an incredible amount of information and has only been used by the original authors to screen for medicinally important metabolites. In this project, I am using the database to find potential trends in host-insect-metabolite relationships e.g.do certain metabolites predict insect presence.

Additional Tidying

There were strange one letter genera and some missing binomials in sciname host, as well as NAs in Order and chemical class (I left the NAs in subclasses because I could still gather information with only class). In the code below, I tidied the data using boolean language in dplyr. I also condensed some of the Subclass 3 categories into their more common names.

genushost_count <- asters %>% count(genushost)
scinamehost_count <- asters %>% count(scinamehost)
genusinsect_count <- asters %>% count(genusinsect)
scinameinsect_count <- asters %>% count(scinameinsect)

Asters <- asters %>%
  filter(!genushost %in% c("A", "H") & 
         !scinamehost %in% c("Achillea", "Helichrysum") & 
         !genusinsect %in% c( "A", "B", "C", "D", "E", "G", "H", "L", "M", "N", "O", "P", "R", "S","T") &  
         !scinameinsect %in% c("Xylocopa") &
         orderinsect != "NA" &
         Class != "NA") %>%
  select(-c("Subclass_4"))%>%
  mutate(Subclass_3 = replace(Subclass_3, Subclass_3 == "C10 isoprenoids (monoterpenes)", "Monoterpenes"))%>%
  mutate(Subclass_3 = replace(Subclass_3, Subclass_3 == "C15 isoprenoids (sesquiterpenes)", "Sesquiterpenes"))%>%
  mutate(Subclass_3 = replace(Subclass_3, Subclass_3 == "C40 isoprenoids (tetraterpenes)", "Tetraterpenes"))%>%
  mutate(Subclass_3 = replace(Subclass_3, Subclass_3 == "C10 isoprenoids (monoterpenes)", "Monoterpenes"))%>%
  mutate(Subclass_3 = replace(Subclass_3, Subclass_3 == "C15 isoprenoids (sesquiterpenes)", "Sesquiterpenes"))%>%
  mutate(Subclass_3 = replace(Subclass_3, Subclass_3 == "C30 isoprenoids (triterpenes)", "Triterpenes"))

One-Hot Encoding the Dataset

Since the variables are categorical and cannot yet be used in the PCoA, I used your template code to create a matrix of insect families by Subclass2 and one-hot encoded the dataset.

#insects-host relationship
fam_insect <- Asters %>% distinct(familyinsect) %>% pull() %>% na.omit()
#chemical subclasses
subclass2 <- Asters%>% distinct(Subclass_2) %>% pull() %>% na.omit()

if(file.exists("output/faminsect_subclass2.csv"))
{
  fam_insect_sub2<- as.matrix(read_csv("output/faminsect_subclass2.csv"))
  rownames(fam_insect_sub2) <- fam_insect
} else
{
  fam_insect_sub2<- matrix(0,nrow = length(fam_insect),ncol = length(subclass2),dimnames = list(fam_insect,  subclass2))
  for(i in 1:length(fam_insect))
  {
    fam_insect_sub2[
      fam_insect[i],
      Asters%>% 
        filter(fam_insect[i] == familyinsect) %>% 
        select(Subclass_2) %>% 
        distinct() %>% 
        pull() %>% 
        na.omit()
    ] <- 1
  }
fam_insect_sub2<- fam_insect_sub2
  rownames(fam_insect_sub2) <- fam_insect
  write_csv(as_tibble(fam_insect_sub2),"output/faminsect_subclass2.csv")

}  

#changing text row names to numbers so it's easier to see on the PCA
row.names(fam_insect_sub2) <- c(1:72)

Running the PCoA

Disclaimer: Im still not fully comfortable with the theory and application of a PCoA, but I included this section regardless since I learned how to use the code and plot it using ggplot. I think these packages will be useful for the future when I understand it better. I ran the PCoA on a matrix with insect families found in Asteraceae on the y-axis and chemical Subclass 2 on the x-axis (which Im not postive is even valid). I tried the PCoA using two packages, one from Principal Coordinate Analysis in R and the other from Distances, then Principal coordinate analysis, clustering, Dendrograms. Both PCoAs looked the same when plotted, but the cmdscale PCoA was more compatible with ggplot, so I chose to show that one. I overlayed the insect orders on top of the family points. I read of ways to include ellipses in PCAs, but couldnt find great code for PCoAs and didnt know if I could use the PCA code. It does look like insects of the Order Lepidoptera may cluster.

#PCoA with cmdscale() stats package
